---- 5.3) Walk Through The Key Visuals
Total Loan Application as a KPI (Key Performance Indicator) is to measure how well a bank or financial system is performing in attracting and processing loan requests.

Total Funded Amount KPI represents the actual amount of money that has been approved and disbursed to borrowers—not just applied for, but truly given out.

Total Amount Received KPI represents the money the bank has actually collected back from borrowers—this includes loan repayments (principal + interest).

Average Interest Rate KPI shows the typical interest rate the bank is charging across all its loans. Instead of looking at each loan separately, it gives one summarized number.

Average Debt-to-Income (DTI) Ratio KPI shows how much of a borrower’s income is already being used to pay debts, averaged across all customers.

The purpose of calculating Good Loan Application % and Bad Loan Application % as KPIs is to clearly measure the quality and risk level of your loan portfolio in a simple,
easy-to-understand way.

The purpose of calculating Good Loan Application KPI and Bad Loan Application KPI is to understand the quality of loan decisions and the overall health of lending operations in a very clear 
and measurable way.

The Good Loan Funded Amount and Bad Loan Funded Amount KPIs are used to measure how much money is actually exposed to safe vs risky loans after the bank has already disbursed funds.

The Good Loan Total Received Amount and Bad Loan Total Received Amount KPIs are used to measure how much money has actually been recovered from safe vs risky loans after disbursement.

The Monthly Trends by Issue Date for Total Funded Amount (Area Chart) KPI is used to track how much money the bank is actually lending out each month over time.

The Regional Analysis by State for Total Funded Amount KPI is used to understand where the bank is lending its money geographically and how lending is distributed across different states.

The Loan Term Analysis (Donut Chart) for Total Funded Amount KPI is used to understand how the bank’s total loan money is distributed across different loan durations (terms), 
such as short-term, medium-term, and long-term loans.

The Employee Length Analysis (Bar Chart) by Total Funded Amount KPI is used to understand how much loan money is being given to borrowers based on their years of employment.

The Loan Purpose by Total Funded Amount (Bar Chart) KPI is used to understand why people are borrowing money and how much money is being allocated to each loan purpose.

The Home Ownership by Total Funded Amount (Treemap) KPI is used to understand how loan money is distributed based on borrowers’ housing status (for example: rent, mortgage, own).


